      "id": 1,
      "text": "Grahamsville takes its name from Revolutionary War officer Lieutenant John Graham, who was killed near the site in 1778.",
      "sourceSentenceIds": [
        7
      ],
      "sourceLabels": [
        "Web source 2"
      ],
      "source": "https://grokipedia.com/page/grahamsville_new_york"
    },
    {
      "id": 2,
      "text": "After 80 years of prohibition, Grahamsville served its first legal drink on December 17, 2015, at the Eureka Market & Café.",
      "sourceSentenceIds": [
        6,
        15
      ],
      "sourceLabels": [
        "Web source 2"
      ],
      "source": "https://grokipedia.com/page/grahamsville_new_york"
    },
    {
      "id": 3,
      "text": "The Time and the Valleys Museum, founded in 2004, preserves Catskills watershed history, reservoir displacements, and 1930s rural life.",
      "sourceSentenceIds": [
        1
      ],
      "sourceLabels": [
        "Web source 2"
      ],
      "source": "https://grokipedia.com/page/grahamsville_new_york"
    },
    {
      "id": 4,
      "text": "Grahamsville Historic District, listed on the National Register, spans about twenty acres and includes a church, cemetery, and former general store.",
      "sourceSentenceIds": [
        26,
        27
      ],
      "sourceLabels": [
        "Web source 1"
      ],
      "source": "https://www.livingplaces.com/NY/Sullivan_County/Neversink_Town/Grahamsville_Historic_District.html"
    },
    {
      "id": 5,
      "text": "Situated near the western end of Rondout Reservoir, Grahamsville is the southernmost community in the Catskill Park.",
      "sourceSentenceIds": [
        10
      ],
      "sourceLabels": [
        "Wikipedia"
      ],
      "source": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Grahamsville%2C_New_York"
    },
    {
      "id": 6,
      "text": "Chestnut Creek, a five‑mile stream running through Grahamsville’s watershed, feeds directly into Rondout Reservoir, supporting trout and diverse macroinvertebrates.",
